In a recently published study, scientists reported that prehistoric birds dating nearly as far back as the dinosaurs were most likely capable of sensing vibrations with their beaks.

The ancient hunting method has been passed down to just a select few. https://t.co/2vJDEyUFMW
text.6:
More puzzlingly, other birds like ostriches and emus have beaks with a similar interior structure, but don’t use the same method to hunt.

The cells are missing. https://t.co/2vJDEyUFMW https://t.co/J1pTYhtB6v
text.7:
As it happens, these birds’ beaks are threaded with cells that can detect vibrations.

Some birds can feel movement directly, while others pick up on waves bouncing off buried shells — echolocating like a dolphin or a bat. https://t.co/2vJDEyUFMW https://t.co/jNJbOjI8GG
